TY  - JOUR
T1  - Attention as the Mediator Between Top Management Team Characteristics and Strategic Change:  The Case of Airline Deregulation
AU  - Cho, Theresa S.
AU  - Hambrick, Donald C.
Y1  - 2006/08/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/orsc.1060.0192
DO  - 10.1287/orsc.1060.0192
T2  - Organization Science
JF  - Organization Science
JO  - Organization Science
SP  - 453
EP  - 469
VL  - 17
IS  - 4
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We integrate the upper-echelons perspective with the attention-based view of the firm by examining the role of attentional orientation of top management teams (TMTs). In the context of airline deregulation, we find that deregulation caused a shift in managerial attention, but that this shift in attention was the greatest for firms that changed the composition and compensation of their TMTs in ways that favored the deregulated regime. We also find that attention partially mediated the relationship between TMT changes and strategy changes. The results of this study shed light on the transformation of industry attention patterns following an environmental shift, and the role of TMT composition and incentive systems in that process.
AB  - We integrate the upper-echelons perspective with the attention-based view of the firm by examining the role of attentional orientation of top management teams (TMTs). In the context of airline deregulation, we find that deregulation caused a shift in managerial attention, but that this shift in attention was the greatest for firms that changed the composition and compensation of their TMTs in ways that favored the deregulated regime. We also find that attention partially mediated the relationship between TMT changes and strategy changes. The results of this study shed light on the transformation of industry attention patterns following an environmental shift, and the role of TMT composition and incentive systems in that process.
